HAGEL, Former U.S. Defense

21:19.111 --> 21:25.651 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Secretary: Assad is a very bad
guy. There are bad guys all over

21:25.684 --> 21:30.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the world. But I think it's
pretty clear that ISIS

21:30.756 --> 21:36.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
represents the real threat to
our country, to the world. GWEN

21:36.328 --> 21:39.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IFILL: President Obama is
scheduled meet with French

21:39.331 --> 21:42.134 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Francois Hollande
tomorrow to discuss the

21:42.168 --> 21:47.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
coalition's next steps. So what
should the U.S. do and what

22:40.192 --> 22:43.596 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shouldn't it do? We have two
views. Former U.S. Ambassador to

22:43.629 --> 22:46.765 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Iraq James Jeffrey served in the
infantry, and he is now a

22:46.799 --> 22:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
distinguished fellow at the
Washington Institute. And John

22:49.702 --> 22:52.671 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mearsheimer, a West Point
graduate and former Air Force

22:52.705 --> 22:55.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
officer, he writes extensively
on strategic issues and is a

22:55.841 --> 22:58.677 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
political science professor at
the University of Chicago.

22:58.711 --> 23:00.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Welcome to you both, gentlemen.
JAMES JEFFREY, Former U.S.

23:00.879 --> 23:02.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ambassador to Iraq: Thank you.
GWEN IFILL: Jim Jeffrey, let's

23:02.881 --> 23:05.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
break this up into two parts,
the military and diplomatic

23:05.317 --> 23:08.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
options. We hear a lot about
boots on the ground, commitment

23:08.754 --> 23:12.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of U.S. forces. Is that the only
thing we should be thinking

23:12.291 --> 23:14.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about? Is that where the debate
is right now? JAMES JEFFREY: In

23:14.660 --> 23:20.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
terms of taking down ISIS as a
state and as an army, we have to

23:20.232 --> 23:23.602 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go on the offensive. That
requires ground troops. We have

23:23.636 --> 23:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tried for 15 months to create a
set of ground troops from the

23:28.274 --> 23:30.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
units and entities and forces on
the ground that we have. It

23:30.276 --> 23:32.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
isn't working all that well. We
don't have the time to keep

23:32.278 --> 23:34.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
trying to do this. Some
insertion of U.S. forces, both

23:34.280 --> 23:36.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as advisers, special forces and
some ground maneuver units are

23:36.282 --> 23:38.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
absolutely necessary to move
this forward. GWEN IFILL:

23:38.284 --> 23:40.619 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Quantify what you mean by some.
JAMES JEFFREY: Well, General

23:40.653 --> 23:46.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jack Keane in congressional
testimony on the 18th talked

23:46.692 --> 23:53.365 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
about two brigades to be
deployed, and that would be

23:53.399 --> 23:58.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about 10,000 combat troops to
stand by to move forward if

24:01.073 --> 24:05.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
needed as we try this expanded
incremental approach that the

24:05.577 --> 24:08.213 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
president is suggesting. GWEN
IFILL: John Mearsheimer, this is

24:08.247 --> 24:11.450 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
called having skin in the game,
theoretically. What are the

24:11.483 --> 24:13.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opportunities for that and what
are the risks? JOHN MEARSHEIMER,

24:13.852 --> 24:16.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
University of Chicago: Well, I
think there is virtually no

24:16.188 --> 24:19.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
chance that we're going to put
large-scale ground forces in

24:19.325 --> 24:23.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Syria, and President Obama has
made it clear that he's not

24:23.162 --> 24:25.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to do that. And the
principal reason is you would

24:25.764 --> 24:29.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have to put a lot of ground
troops in to defeat ISIS. And

24:29.468 --> 24:33.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there is no question that if you
put 100,000, 150,000 troops in

24:34.006 --> 24:35.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there, you could defeat ISIS,
but then you run into the

24:36.008 --> 24:38.877 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what-next question. What are we
going to do, stay in there and

24:38.911 --> 24:41.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
occupy the place? And the end
result will be dealing with

24:41.580 --> 24:44.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
insurgents, won't know how to
get out and will just make a bad

24:44.883 --> 24:48.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
situation worse. So it's quite
clear to me that there is no way

24:48.520 --> 24:52.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we can defeat ISIS from the air
or with ground forces. And,

24:52.758 --> 24:55.461 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
therefore, we have to find some
sort of diplomatic solution.

24:55.494 --> 24:58.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, before we get
to the diplomatic, what are the

24:58.263 --> 25:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
options here? Are we talking
about occupation? Is that

25:01.333 --> 25:05.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inevitable? JOHN MEARSHEIMER:
No, occupation is not

25:05.104 --> 25:09.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inevitable. And I don't believe
we will end up occupying Syria,

25:09.808 --> 25:13.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because we have tried this
before, in both Afghanistan and

25:13.479 --> 25:16.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Iraq, and it didn't turn out
very well. And we would be

25:16.815 --> 25:20.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
remarkably foolish to try to
duplicate that task. And there

25:20.853 --> 25:23.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is no way we can win this one
with airpower alone. The only

25:23.956 --> 25:29.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hope is that Assad's forces can
be rebuilt, to the point where

25:29.428 --> 25:32.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they can deal with ISIS, and
then we can get out of the

25:32.464 --> 25:34.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
region militarily. GWEN IFILL:
Let me ask you both this

25:34.933 --> 25:38.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
question. You know that Francois
Hollande is coming to Washington

25:38.103 --> 25:40.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tomorrow, going to meet with the
president. What should he be

25:40.105 --> 25:42.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
asking for? JAMES JEFFREY: What
he will be asking for is a far

25:42.875 --> 25:46.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
more aggressive American
campaign against ISIS, because,

25:46.578 --> 25:50.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if he doesn't get a yes, an
affirmative answer to that, he's

25:50.282 --> 25:53.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to in any case go off to
Moscow and ask the same thing of

25:53.318 --> 25:57.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Putin. Putin has perhaps
one-tenth of our military

25:57.289 --> 26:00.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
capabilities, but Putin will
give him an affirmative on a

26:00.759 --> 26:03.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very aggressive campaign against
ISIS. So, we're going to have

26:03.328 --> 26:05.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that one way or the other. GWEN
IFILL: John Mearsheimer, what do

26:05.364 --> 26:08.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you think that Hollande should
be or will be asking for? JOHN

26:08.033 --> 26:10.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MEARSHEIMER: Well, first of all,
I think that what he should ask

26:10.903 --> 26:15.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for is a coalition that includes
the United States, the Russians,

26:15.707 --> 26:19.511 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Iran and a number of other
actors in the region to work for

26:19.545 --> 26:23.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the purposes of propping up the
Assad government. The only hope

26:23.315 --> 26:27.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have here is to prop up Assad
and make him powerful enough

26:27.920 --> 26:30.889 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that he can deal with ISIS. That
way, we don't have to put in

26:30.923 --> 26:33.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ground forces. And the Russians
of course are not going to put

26:33.492 --> 26:38.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in ground forces themselves. So
the only hope is Assad. But the

26:38.363 --> 26:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
principal problem we face is
that the United States is

26:41.099 --> 26:44.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
incapable of working with the
Russians. We still continue to

26:44.536 --> 26:47.973 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pursue this policy where we're
trying to topple Assad and the

26:48.006 --> 26:51.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Russians are trying to support
Assad. This is crazy, because

26:51.343 --> 26:54.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we're working at cross-purposes
and, if anything, we're just

26:54.279 --> 26:57.082 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to make the war worse and
that is going to play to ISIS'

26:57.116 --> 27:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
advantage. I think Hollande
understands this. GWEN IFILL:

27:00.486 --> 27:02.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let me stay with you, Mr.
Mearsheimer, for a moment,

27:02.488 --> 27:04.456 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because you brought up the
question of diplomatic

27:04.490 --> 27:07.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
solutions. Do we have time to
pursue that? We're right in the

27:07.559 --> 27:10.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
middle of this now. JOHN
MEARSHEIMER: Well, we really

27:10.729 --> 27:13.632 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have no choice. There is no
simple military solution. There

27:13.665 --> 27:16.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is nothing the Americans or the
Russians can do militarily to

27:16.702 --> 27:19.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
win this, because we're not
willing to commit ground forces,

27:19.171 --> 27:22.908 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for good reasons. So, what we
have to do is, we have to work

27:22.941 --> 27:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with Assad and we have to create
a situation where he's powerful

27:27.179 --> 27:31.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
enough to push back ISIS and
then work to get some sort of

27:31.650 --> 27:35.587 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
peace settlement in the region.
It's going to be remarkably

27:35.621 --> 27:38.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
difficult to do, in large part
because, as I said, the

27:38.790 --> 27:42.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Americans are incapable of
working with the Russians. GWEN

27:42.060 --> 27:46.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IFILL: Ambassador Jeffrey, let's
talk about this Assad question.

27:46.832 --> 27:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's clear that we're not on the
same side of the discussion with

27:48.834 --> 27:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Russia on Assad. And you just
heard what Mr. Mearsheimer said

27:50.836 --> 27:54.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about, hey, listen, let's forget
about this idea of ousting Assad

27:54.573 --> 27:57.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for now. What do you think?
JAMES JEFFREY: Gwen, in this

27:57.142 --> 28:00.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
business, we can never be
totally sure, but I'm about as

28:00.279 --> 28:03.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sure as I ever can be that, if
we tried to throw our weight

28:03.415 --> 28:07.486 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
behind this unholy coalition of
Assad, the Russians and the

28:07.519 --> 28:11.490 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Iranians, we would ensure that
ISIS will not only survive, but

28:11.523 --> 28:15.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
prosper, because the entire Arab
Sunni world and Turkey will

28:15.561 --> 28:19.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
throw their weight against us on
this. This is a double-barreled

28:19.765 --> 28:23.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
problem we have, the Assad
regime, which helped create ISIS

28:23.802 --> 28:28.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and is now supported by Russia
and Iran, and ISIS itself. The

28:28.106 --> 28:31.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way to do this is to keep Assad
out of the battle and take the

28:31.610 --> 28:36.615 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fight to ISIS. ISIS has 30,000
troops. We have about 200,000 or

28:38.650 --> 28:41.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
300,000 of our allied troops,
but they don't have the

28:41.887 --> 28:43.956 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
capability to take the offensive
without America leading. GWEN

28:43.989 --> 28:46.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IFILL: Let me ask you. And I
want to ask this also to Mr.

28:46.592 --> 28:50.362 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Mearsheimer. What is our
long-term or even our short-term

28:50.395 --> 28:55.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
strategic objective in Syria?
Why should we be more involved?

28:55.067 --> 28:57.336 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES JEFFREY: First of all...
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: Well, I

28:57.369 --> 28:59.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think... JAMES JEFFREY: ... it's
in the center of the Middle

28:59.371 --> 29:01.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
East. Secondly, we have allies
to the north in Turkey, to the

29:01.373 --> 29:04.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
south in Israel and Jordan, and
we have extraordinary interests

29:04.643 --> 29:07.613 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that President Obama has
emphasized time and time again.

29:07.646 --> 29:10.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He acknowledges that we are
fighting a war against ISIS. His

29:10.849 --> 29:13.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
goal is to destroy it. He said
that again yesterday. The

29:13.619 --> 29:17.556 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
question is how to do that. And
our long-term goals are to try

29:17.589 --> 29:21.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to bring some kind of
resurrection of the state system

29:21.727 --> 29:24.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in these very, very fragile
countries, because they can't

29:24.262 --> 29:26.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stand up against these movements
otherwise. GWEN IFILL: John

29:26.965 --> 29:29.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mearsheimer? JOHN MEARSHEIMER:
First of all, I don't believe

29:29.201 --> 29:32.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that the United States has any
strategic interest in Syria. I

29:32.671 --> 29:36.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think, from a strategic point of
view, Syria is an insignificant

29:36.341 --> 29:39.811 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country. It's not like Iraq or
Iran that have lots of oil.

29:39.845 --> 29:44.583 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Second, I think the principal
two reasons that we should want

29:44.616 --> 29:48.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to shut down this conflict as
soon as possible is, number one,

29:48.453 --> 29:51.490 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for humanitarian reasons -- this
is a human rights disaster --

29:51.523 --> 29:55.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and, secondly, because if we
don't stem the flow of refugees

29:55.260 --> 29:58.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into Europe, it's going to cause
all sorts of problems in Europe.

29:58.497 --> 30:00.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You can already see that
happening. So we have a

30:00.799 --> 30:03.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deep-seated interest, I think
not for strategic reasons, but

30:03.535 --> 30:06.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for human rights reasons and
because of Europe, to do what we

30:06.538 --> 30:09.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can to end this one as quickly
as possible. But I don't think

30:09.808 --> 30:13.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's going to happen, because
I think the ambassador's view of

30:13.078 --> 30:17.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dealing with the Russians is
correct in the minds of most

30:17.282 --> 30:20.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Americans. And most people
disagree with what I say. And,

30:20.519 --> 30:24.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
therefore, we won't work with
the Russians and we won't solve

30:24.089 --> 30:27.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this problem. It will only get
worse. More Syrians will die and

30:28.026 --> 30:30.896 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more refugees will go into
Europe. GWEN IFILL: Interesting

30:30.929 --> 30:33.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
listening to you argue against
your own point of view there.

30:33.398 --> 30:36.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Professor Mearsheimer of the
University of Chicago, thank you

30:36.234 --> 30:39.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very much, and to Ambassador Jim
Jeffrey here in Washington. JOHN

30:39.471 --> 30:44.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MEARSHEIMER: Thank you. GWEN
IFILL: The debate over what role

30:54.586 --> 30:57.556 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the U.S. should play in the
fight against ISIS has also

30:57.589 --> 31:01.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
become central to the 2016
campaign. But how are the

31:01.359 --> 31:04.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
candidates talking about it?
Political director Lisa

31:04.196 --> 31:08.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Desjardins reports. LISA
DESJARDINS: Welcome to campaign

31:08.700 --> 31:10.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
national security, with the
Islamic State group at the

31:10.702 --> 31:12.671 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
center. SEN. MARCO RUBIO (R-FL),
Presidential Candidate: They are

31:12.704 --> 31:15.207 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
growing. They're in Afghanistan.
ISIS is now on the ground in

31:15.240 --> 31:18.977 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Afghanistan recruiting Taliban
fighters away from the Taliban.

31:19.010 --> 31:22.447 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're radical killers. And
either they win or we win. LISA

31:22.481 --> 31:25.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DESJARDINS: Many candidates,
like Marco Rubio today in Iowa,

31:25.650 --> 31:29.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are pouncing on fears about ISIS
to flex ideological and

31:29.788 --> 31:33.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
political muscle. Republicans in
particular have strong

31:33.358 --> 31:37.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
